{
  "narrative": "Benjamin set out to build a Claude Code session summarizer—a tool to understand how he's using AI and track code changes without burning through tokens. What started as a straightforward CLI evolved into a full-featured web application through deliberate iteration and team collaboration. Early on, he discovered that Claude Code stores all session data as JSONL files in `~/.claude/`, including prompts, responses, and tool output. Rather than just parsing and displaying raw data, he pivoted to use Claude's API for AI-powered summarization, generating narratives and tutorial walkthroughs that actually communicate insight. The HTML reports were initially overdesigned and confusing, so he spawned a team of agents to tackle the problem from multiple angles—a PM wrote the product spec, a UX designer created wireframes and a React scaffold, and backend/frontend devs built an Express API and full React UI. Mid-session he killed the Electron/Tauri experimentation and settled on a simple web app, then hardened security (port 51778, localhost-only, path traversal protection), made it `npx`-launchable with automatic browser opening, added localStorage-based API key management with onboarding banners, implemented disk caching for summaries, and finally built a separate Express-based file-sharing service (deployable to Coolify) so users can share sanitized session summaries with delete tokens—solving the real UX problem of how to safely share insights without exposing sensitive data.",
  "tutorialSteps": [
    {
      "title": "Research Claude Code's data model",
      "description": "Benjamin explored `~/.claude/projects/` and discovered JSONL session files with full conversation history, tool calls, and outputs. This research (turns 9-15) established that the raw data was available locally without needing API access.",
      "turnRange": "9-15",
      "keyTakeaway": "Understanding where data actually lives and what format it's in is the foundation for any analysis tool—no need to guess or overcomplicate architecture."
    },
    {
      "title": "Build a fast parser and analyzer pipeline",
      "description": "He wrote `parser.ts` to extract sessions from the filesystem, `analyzer.ts` to compute metrics (turn counts, token estimates, code changes), and `report.ts` to generate HTML. This CLI tool (turns 20-27) proved the concept before building a UI.",
      "turnRange": "20-27",
      "keyTakeaway": "Getting a working CLI prototype first lets you validate the core logic independently of UI complexity."
    },
    {
      "title": "Pivot from data display to AI-powered insights",
      "description": "Initial HTML reports just reformatted raw JSONL—no value. He integrated the Anthropic SDK (turns 48-50), built `summarize.ts` to generate narratives and tutorial steps, and completely redesigned the report to lead with insights rather than raw data. This required fixing JSON parsing issues with Haiku's markdown-wrapped responses (turns 104-117).",
      "turnRange": "48-117",
      "keyTakeaway": "Raw data in fancy HTML is still just noise. Real value comes from applying AI to synthesize and teach, not just format."
    },
    {
      "title": "Abandon dashboard UX, embrace scroll-based documents",
      "description": "The first sophisticated report design (with tabs, sidebars, and dashboard elements) was overdesigned and confusing. After feedback and team input (turns 120-143), he scrapped it for a simple single-column scroll-based document aesthetic with proper typography and hierarchy.",
      "turnRange": "120-143",
      "keyTakeaway": "Elegant simplicity beats feature-rich complexity. A session summary is a document, not a dashboard—design accordingly."
    },
    {
      "title": "Spawn a team to parallelize the web app build",
      "description": "Rather than building everything sequentially, he created a team with PM, UX Designer, Backend Dev, and Frontend Dev roles (turns 169-223). The PM wrote the product spec, UX created a design system and React scaffold, backend built the Express API, and frontend connected the views. This cut development time significantly through parallelization.",
      "turnRange": "169-223",
      "keyTakeaway": "For larger features, spawning agents for different roles lets you work on multiple parts in parallel—great for complex projects."
    },
    {
      "title": "Simplify distribution with a single `npx` command",
      "description": "Instead of Electron or Tauri complexity, he realized the best distribution model was a single entry point: running `npx claude-code-summary` starts an Express server on port 51778, serves the built React app, and opens the browser automatically (turns 353-392). This requires no installation beyond Node.js, which most developers have.",
      "turnRange": "353-392",
      "keyTakeaway": "Sometimes the simplest distribution is just a Node.js server. If your target user has npm, `npx` is friction-free."
    },
    {
      "title": "Add security hardening and local caching",
      "description": "He locked down the server (localhost-only binding, path traversal validation with regex, obscure port 51778 to avoid collisions), added localStorage-based API key management so users provide their own Anthropic credentials (turns 356-368), and implemented disk caching in `~/.claude/ccs-cache/` so AI summaries persist across server restarts (turns 416-424).",
      "turnRange": "356-424",
      "keyTakeaway": "Security isn't an afterthought—validate paths, bind to localhost, use env vars for secrets, and cache intelligently to reduce API costs."
    },
    {
      "title": "Design a simple sharing model instead of full hosting",
      "description": "Rather than building a full Phoenix/database-backed app, he created a lightweight file-sharing service (`share-server/`) deployable to Coolify. Users upload sanitized summaries, get a shareable link, and can delete them later from their local app using a delete token (turns 428-451). This solved the real problem: how to share insights safely without exposing sensitive data or requiring logins.",
      "turnRange": "428-451",
      "keyTakeaway": "Answer the actual user need first. Sharing doesn't require a full web app—sometimes a simple file server with delete tokens is better than complex auth and databases."
    }
  ],
  "efficiencyInsights": [
    "The first 50 turns involved a lot of iterative re-designs of the report HTML/CSS. Starting with a proper UX/design spec earlier (like the PM did) would have prevented the thrashing—write the spec before building the UI.",
    "Spawning the team was great, but the team initially waited on the PM for the product spec before starting. Using your standard PRODUCT_SPEC.md template upfront would have unblocked everyone immediately.",
    "The Electron → Tauri → 'just a web app' pivoting (turns 269-348) cost ~80 turns of thrashing. A quick 'what are you really distributing?' conversation at the start would have saved that time.",
    "Integrating the Anthropic API key from environment variables was done late. Doing that during the parser/analyzer phase would have let him test `--ai` summarization much earlier, avoiding the markdown-wrapping JSON parse bugs.",
    "The share-server was built after the main app was 'done.' Building the sharing model and user flow earlier would have informed the app's architecture—e.g., what data to redact, how summaries should be structured for sharing, etc."
  ],
  "highlights": [
